review: Winter isn't over and the idea of winter making everything else--well, ridiculous--fits reading this book. I spent a day in bed, after the thaw that wWinter isn't over and the idea of winter making everything else--well, ridiculous--fits reading this book. I spent a day in bed, after the thaw that was a fooling kind of thaw because it caused another freeze, and read this book. I laughed and forgot about my seasonal depression. What more can you ask for from a book sometimes? A good day in bed, a good day to forget the bone chills. The writing, since this is a book  and not a seasonal investigation (though you might notice the title and the relationship to seasonal depression light boxes), is quirky, but covering up some pretty dark themes. Not unlike a dream in its haziness--something "cloudy" about the writing, something uncertain that seems to fit the very content of the text. I mean to say, the writing pulls at it's own sparsity, shows the difficulty of creating a fable that seems...well, possible. And it is possible because it's a bit confusing, a bit unnerving, and a bit of a refusal to tell a clear and exact story. It's not exact. It's not clear. It's hazy. It's hazy because it's truths and subtext are important and interesting. How can we say important and interesting things clearly?...more
